name: Kelly Bone
bio:
San Diego 
Everything is vegan ☺️
No ads or sponsored posts
Bylines: Eater SD
Just Pizza @veganpizzabone
Also @veganinsandiego @firstfridaynightmarket

social_posts.post_text:
Through meat is the namesake of Shaking Beef salad, it's the easiest ingredient to replace. Designed for a world scarce of meat (a reality of the past and a requirement of the future), this salad's essence forms between bitter watercress, fresh cucumbers, and tomatoes all experiencing the first stages of wilting under the warm sweet soy, citrus, salt and pepper juice dripping from a protein and seared sweet onions. Sub out any of these vegetables and the allure that makes me stop at Bồ Đề Tịnh Tâm Chay nearly every time I pass through Orange County, dissipates.

This bold plate (176. An lạc lúc lắc - $14) stands above all other dishes here (I say facetiously since I've eaten less than 5% of the menu because I keep ordering this salad). I see Shaking Beef appear on tables across the dining room and assure myself that all of us, strangers, have reached the same conclusion.

#VeganVietnamese
#VeganShakingBeed
#VeganSalad 
@bodetinhtamchay

Every First Friday you'll find me at @firstfridaynightmarket at @grossmontcenter trying to capture a little bit of everything.

#FirstFridayNightMarket #FirstFridayNightMarketSD #VeganinSanDiego #VeganNightMarket #SanDiegoNightMarket #SanDiegoVegan #VeganinSanDiego #SanDiegoEvents

Though @mendocinofarms continues to whittle away at their vegan options* the single sandwich that remands, the Vegan Banh Mi ($11.5), is better than what's left of the vegan sandwich options at neighboring (and minority stakeholder) Whole Foods/Amazon.

Unapologetically unauthentic, ciabatta bread is filled with baked tofu, pickled carrots and daikon, jalapeno, basil, cilantro, cucumber, and loaded with sweet chili sauce and mayo. It's a sweet messy sandwich and I saw many strangers ordering it before and after me. I added a side of the curry couscous ($3.1) because I was feeling extra and willing to pay for my feelings.

* RIP: vegan reuben, BBQ tempeh, quinoa chickpea burger, chickpea spinach patty, samosa wrap, falafel wrap, tempeh lettuce and tomato, mushroom burger, soyrizo wrap, avocado toast, dill pickle potato salad, spring roll salad, healthiest side salad ever, and so on... 

#MendocinoFarms
#VeganBanhMi
#TofuSandwich

There are some nights where, yes, I take photos but otherwise focus on being present.... And such nights sometimes get skipped online.

But @donnajeanofficial deserves a trip back in time, to a cool March night when I celebrated my birthday on their starry patio. Fluttering leaves and kind service carried us through a four course meal, with nearly every dish loaded with local @scratchhousesd cheese. From the Fungazi pizza ($22) studded with duxelles mushrooms, spinach, and truffle cream, to the Really Good Salad ($15) sporting pickled raisins, shaved radish, mozzarella, and pistachios in a roasted garlic dressing, all are delicate delights.

My favorite here remains the pasta course. Proving perfect pasta needs no eggs, @royelam's vegan handmade program continues to awe (want to learn more? Definitely take one of his classes). I collapsed into this pillowy pile of end-of-winter squash and lacinato kale with a crunchy sprinkle of pepitas and shaved SH parmesan. I could eat this dish 100 times and still want more.

The meal was finished off with a Double Chocolate Oat Brownie ($12) crowded in coco whip, caramel sauce, and a candle paired with a silent moment to make a wish.

#DonnaJeanSD
#VegsninSanDiego 
#VeganPizzainSanDiego

Seeped in black garlic vinaigrette, thick cuts of King Trumpet Mushroom feathered with fresh herbs and chimichurri ($15) at @herbandwood could easily, EASILY, anchor a main dish. Instead, the wise diner will order them from the vegetable menu.

Every main needs a side. A few salads can be modified vegan, like the Roasted Beets and Strawberries ($16, hold the cheese) with preserved lemon vinaigrette and crisp watercress. Or go hardy with the Seven Spiced Cauilini ($17 vegan as is) piled high over fried chickpeas, hummus, apricots, and curry leaves.

Right now, one dollar for each king trumpet mushrooms ordered will be donated to local San Diego nonprofit @berrygoodfoodfdn. So go on, and make them your main while sitting on their fire lit patio with a cocktail and a scoop of gelato... or two or three...

#HerbandWood
#KingTrumpetMushrooms 
#VegetableMainDish

If you haven't heard yet, @nativefoodscafe in San Diego's Clairmont is closing (along with Westwood in LA and Costa Mesa in the OC)

If you were vegetarian or vegan in the 90's/2000's in Southern California you most likely ate at Native Foods, frequently. Once a populated chain through the region, after June 10th San Diego's Point Loma and the original Palm Springs location (and a ghost kitchen on the OC) will be the last ones left in CA. So, if you're a fan, treasure them because frankly I don't know a single other spot in San Diego serving a house-made seitan burger... a burger patty form far superior to any Impossible or Beyond and without the smush factor of bean and grain burgers.

I always go for the BBQ Brisket Burger ($14.95) topped with house-made seitan brisket, bbq sauce, vegan cheese, coleslaw, and onions rings (hold the mayo, it's completely unnecessary on this burger). I usually balance it out with a side of steamed kale but decided to try the loaded baked potato salad which is mostly loaded with completely unnecessary mayo. Still, I'm happy to try a new thing as I count down the days to losing my favorite location.

#NativeFoods
#SeitanBurger
#VeganinSanDiego

Mothership is not an everyday kind of place and it does not serve everyday food.

While @intothevoidinc cocktails follow the rum forward-formulas of Tiki menus past, the food is intentionally obtuse.

A spiral bound book offers basic names, like "Potato" and "Rice" and lists the ingredients, but the plates that arrive are not obvious conclusions. Without the context of "I'm at an Italian restaurant" or "I'm in Peru," there is little for your imagination to pull assumptions from. By design! 

This is science fiction on a plate–universal Earth fusion meant to captivate and hold you in the story for your 90 minute reservation.

We ordered the entire menu. Which is fun to say, but there are only 6 dishes so it was the obvious choice for a table of 4. My favorite (and the favorite of the internet commenting community) was Potato ($15). Deep fried triangles of shredded white flesh laced with scallions. Each piece is spotted with pink kimchi cream cheese holding a sliver of black radish and sprinkled with everything furikake (seemingly, a blend of sesame, poppy, garlic, and seaweed). Finished with young nasturtium leaves and thin cuts of japanese cucumber, this dish speaks to the universal love, and survivalist nature, of this humanity saving tuber.

#IntoTheVoid
#SienceFictionFood
#VeganInSanDiego

Comedy is me trying to explain what tteok is to @carlyisvegan while entangled in a fictitious intergalactic calamity turned permanent vacation called Mothership @intothevoidinc. Because if you're not familiar with these thick chewy rice cakes/dumpling it's hard to envision this gnocchi looking dish arriving when ordering "Rice" ($19). The "rice" is dressed in hunter green aji verde (a Peruvian chili sauce) made less Peruvian with lemongrass and crowded with crispy shallots and cucumber.

Noodles ($16) is the only straightforward dish. Fresh egg-free egg noodles sit naked in a pool of Singaporean-style coconut laksa broth (which is similar to Thai red curry, but thinner and not Thai red curry) with curry tofu, a ribbon of pineapple, grilled leafy green gai lan, and purple radishes.

This season's special is Bread ($13), a frozen pizza looking flaky Hungarian flatbread that tastes nothing like pizza. Spread with confit garlic paste and a soft pedigreedless vegan cheese with dots of Sicillian sweet and sour agrodolce. If you know your food history, then you recognize that sauce holds the history of people different, but not that different, from us who too settled in a strange land but couldn't hide a longing for home in the foods they made.

#IntoTheVoid
#SiFiFood
#VeganInSanDiego

The strangest part about my trip to Mothership were people afterwards attempting to commiserate with me in "I loved at the bar,  hated the food" conversations. I found the entire experience delightful.

But now that I have tried every dish @intothevoidinc would I order everything again? Nope. My least favorite was Tofu ($17), but not for the reasons I expected. I expected a small slab of marinated tofu (marinading slabs of tofu is a waste of tofu's time #sorrynotsorry), but in this spacetime continuum "tofu" is a complex flakey otak patty–a South Asian fish cake dupe made with all the same seasoning with shredded tofu instead of fish and grilled in a banana leaf. Very convincing! If just the thought of fish as food didn't turn my stomach upside down I would have adored this deep sea delight. 

Pancake ($16) was another I'd likely not order again. I love Chinese scallion pancakes and Japanese okonomiyaki–this doughy cross between the two didn't have the delicate magic of either. But it is the most filling and most attractive of the dishes presented, which has its place in a cocktail world.

Another complaint I've heard is that the drinks "are all ice." While it is true that each glass is brimming with pebble ice, the glasses themselves are oversized. One lasted me the whole 90 minute reservation. @mrvegan_in_sandiego Mindkiller ($18) was a JOB to finish. We all attempted to help but it felt like one of those trick glasses that keeps refining itself.

#IntoTheVoid
#SiFiFood
#VeganInSanDiego

A beautiful northern Thai dish, Kow Soi ($15) is soooo almost vegan at most places it hurts. A rich coconut curry–that falls somewhere between a turmeric rich yellow curry and the warming spices of massaman–pooled around wheat noodles and protein (tofu is a perfectly common choice) topped with pickled mustard greens, shallots (in this case red onion), cilantro, lime and a wild crown of crispy noodles. @veganicthaicafe is the one place in San Diego that makes this vegan... Why is it not vegan at other places? The noodles.

This dish is traditionally made with egg noodles. But wheat noodles are one of the few foods I am comfortable arguing taste just as good made with water over eggs. Swapping out eggless noodles is no sacrifice to flavor. I know it's just as good because for a brief moment another restaurant in San Diego claimed on their menu to make vegan Kow Soi. When I complimented them on the dish, after eating, I was told the dish was made with egg noodles. Veganic's version is just as good, guaranteed egg free, and has quickly become my favorite dish at the restaurant.

#VeganThaiinSanDiego
#VeganThaiFood
#KowSoi

Back in San Diego just in time to grab an @angkorian_pikestaff Vegan Pork Belly Banh Mi ($15). Crispy layers of (I assume) baguette crust, fatty tapioca, and soy are seasoned and compressed into a meaty filling with cucumbers, pickled daikon and carrots, cilantro, jalapenos, and vegan mayo. Absolutely delicious.

If you ever had the chance to love the vegan banh mi at Tiger Tiger, this is Socheath Sun's progression on the dish. The bread is softer, the filling is more flavorful, and the side of vegan "shrimp" chips is... kisses! 

Open only Monday and Tuesday inside of National City’s @marketon8thst, the small menu changes often but almost always includes a vegan option ❤️

#VeganBanhMiinSanDiego
#VeganBanhMi
#BanhMiChay

I'm years late to the @nomaddonuts sandwich board. On first bite of this Baogel ($14) I deeply regretted waiting this long. 

Most of Nomad's bagel sandwiches offer vegan versions. Here meat is swapped with fried eggplant then treated with the same espresso bbq, scallion slaw, pickled onions, and peppers. The beast is dripping with sweet soy and chili oil, collecting in the paper box... I promptly tore off bits of my rosemary seasalt bagel to sop it up because I could not stand the thought of every drop of this sandwich not ending up inside of me.

#VeganSandwichinSanDiego
#BagelSandwich
#VeganSandwich

location.city_name: Goi Cuon Fresh Vietnamese Spring Rolls

social_posts.post_text:
I fell in love with @goicuon.us at the Hillcrest farmers market. Strolling booths of summer lettuce and winter squash with a fist full of fresh summer rolls was a San Diego delight. Then Covid hit and it all went away. Sort of.

No longer at the farmers market, Goi Cuon moved to a permanent home in the heart of Hillcrest. The new space opens the menu to a breath of rolls –fried, fresh, pho roll, crispy crepe (banh xeo) rolls–plus banh mi, rice and noodle dishes. Always mindful of vegan options, the totally vegan as-is Combo 3 ($11.99) is my go to. An assortment of fried treats and brothy soup comes with a Pho roll–tofu and greens wrapped in a thick fresh noodle skin with coconut dip–and an Avocado summer roll with peanut sauce.

It's plenty on its own, but I always add on my hands down favorite item: No.12 the tofu skin and crispy snack fresh roll ($3.95). Peppery yuba (tofu skins) are steamed into a flaky cake, sliced and rolled in a rice paper skin with lettuce and rice noodles, with a pencil thin deep fried wonton wrapper running through its heart. It's a satisfying play of textures that I recommend, without hesitation, to everyone.

#VeganSummerRollsinSanDiego
#SummerRolls 
#VeganVietnameseinSanDiego

As happenstance would have it, the woman in front of me at @gelatiandpeccati asked for vegan cheese to be added to her Marinara slice ($4.25). I scanned the various signs and saw no such notice, but asked for the same and received a generous helping of salty vegan cheese on my Arrabiata slice ($4.25) at no extra charge.

Both vegan options are spread thin with sauce and dotted with cherry tomatoes. The Arrabiata brings a bit of heat to the crunchy top of these Roman-style Pizza al Taglio. As you can see, the temperament of the crust varies between batches, but this remains a quality pizza by the slice option in North Park. While I preferred the un-cheesed slice (each "slice" is cut in half here so it's a rather generous portion per order) know that the vegan cheese is there if you need it 😉😊

#VeganPizzainSanDiego
#PizzaalTaglio
#SanDiegoPizza

My first taste of dolmas were still-warm, hand-rolled, lemon steamed grape leaves stuffed with fresh herbs and fluffy short grain white rice. A culinary delight! To have weened on these  means I will never settle for those straight from a can slimy "dolmas" too often served at restaurants or passed off as "food" by Trader Joe's.

Dolmas thrive on textual layers. Sun ripe leaves preserved in salt, acid, and time turned tender for our dull incisors to pierce. Laid flat, the leaves are filled with rice, still slightly firm–not the mush from a can or the completely separated grains of minute rice. Herbs should scream their names in unison. Loudest are (if you're lucky) dill fronds, followed by cool mints and parsley or warm coriander and pine nuts (or others).

Steamed in lemon and olive oil, even handmade ones run the risk of collapsing into a mono-texture at this stage. The Dolmas ($10.95) at @alforon_sd are perfect. Not because they resemble my nostalgic first taste (they don't) but because they embody the same spirit. They respect the craft (and customer) and I salivate at just the memory of them. Both. 

#VeganLebaneseinSanDiego
#GrapeLeaves
#VeganinSanDiego

Are you a Maximalist or a Minimalist?

Perhaps, like me, you are a little bit of both. @alforon hits with the simple pleasure of thyme and sesame Zaatar ($6.95) flatbread AND an explosion of flavor on the Falafel Bajeen ($12.95).

The Falafel Bajeen is a signature dish of George Salameh's menu. A plant-based eater himself, George takes this traditionally meat spread on bread pie and replaces the raw meat with raw falafel. The whole flatbread is baked and then topped with crisp lettuce, tomato, pickles, and drizzled with tahini and parsley. It's a meal in and of itself but the idea of only ordering one thing when there are so so many vegan items at Alforon is bananas!

#FalafalBajeen
#VeganLebaneseinSanDiego
#Bajeen

There are two ways an omni chef plans their vegan options.

1. As the light, healthy, mild dishes meant to accompany actually filling heavier meat dishes and/or encompassing all the pesky diet people that may stumble through the door (hence why vegan and gluten free are too often mashed together despite having zero in common).

2. As direct alternatives to meat dishes. Designed to deliver the same punch of flavors and leave you feeling full.

Clearly I favor 2, and clearly @makmak_organic does too. The menu is nearly half vegan and anyone can have a full plate of rice, pickles, broth, and protein. The tofu is thin, and pan fried to a crisp in a starchy shell. There are three sauces to choose from, but the extra crisp created by the spicy Thai chili stands out. Served with coconut rice and rich veggie broth I definitely walked away from this dish feeling full.

#SpicyTofu
#VeganinSanDiego
#VeganOceanside

Up early, running around town, I needed to quell my stomach before work. Finding a quick vegan-friendly meal at 8am on a weekend (that doesn't require going way out of one's way) is a challenge in any American city. I'm lucky that there was one: @peetscoffee .

Peet's offers a vegan as-is Everything Plant-based Sandwich ($6.25) with @justegg, @beyondmeat sausage, and @violife_foods cheese. It tastes like the sum of its parts, which is to say it's painstakingly designed to taste good. And while I would have been happy to pay more then double for a locally baked biscuit with fried tofu, eggplant bacon, and tomato... le sigh... that isn't a choice between here and my office. 

#VeganBreakfast
#VeganBreakfastinSanDiego
#PeetsCoffee

An unexpected delight in Lakeside! 

Farther east than I know by heart, and without a heads-up on our lunch destination, I walked blindly into @marys_donuts with a client who doesn't know I'm vegan. Expectations were low, so the sight of "The Vegan" listed on their sandwich board ($13.99) startled my sleeping heart.

The size shocked me next. The container is stuffed with a fat onion loaf loaded with beets, arugula, sprouts, tomatoes, cucumbers, and onions spread  light cilantro sauce and served with a pickle and bag of chips. I can eat a lot of sandwich, but even I couldn't eat all this. 

While not much more than the sum of its part–and would have benefited from the pepperoncini that I didn't see were an optional add on until leaving–this is a gloriously filling lunch to stumble into on a day when I expected nothing.

#VeganSandwichinSanDiego
#Sandwich 
#VeganinSanDiego

A favorite of the farmers market (years ago) @leos_kitchen_sd continues to serve tip top vegetable sushi. You're not going to find any fishy replacements here...All vegan options lean into delicate textures of land. 

The happy hour menu is almost always in effect when dining-in (except for the last hour) and includes favorites like the Baja Lemon ($13.99 or $10 HH). It's a classic veggie roll with julienned carrots, avocado, and cucumber that comes layered in more avocado, paper thin slices of lemon with cilantro, chili, ponzu, and sriracha. Full of flavor, but not too much, this has been my Leo's pick for years 🩷

#VeganSushiinSanDiego
#VeganSushi 
#VegetableSushi

Tomatoes! Glorious tomatoes rulise from the treasure that is San Diego's Chino Farm. 

On a sunny Wednesday I ended up at @paradisaea where vegan options may be limited, but they have this: a juicy pile of fresh tomatoes and confit stone fruit over crispy rice floating in a translucent pool with herb pesto ($25). As I dug into this platter of summer @chinofarms was just a few tables away doing the same. How heavenly, to be served the same batch of tomatoes as the farmer who brought them into this world.

#Tomatoes 
#SummerSalad
#ChinoFarms

location.city_name: POTS n' WOKS chinese food & BOBA

social_posts.post_text:
@potsnwoks is like a waking dream.

Simmering trays hold proteins, noodles, and vegetables all gossy in sweet soy and bright orange sauces. Meals come in trays of one two or three scoops of your choice of entree.... and in a move I've never experienced as a vegan, there are more than max per plate to choose from. While the vegan options run deeper than the six prepared, like most Americans I often do not have the time for made to order food.

The quality is a step to the side rather than a step up from the obvious comparison, Panda Express. But that's the point! This food combines the same nostalgic recipes and gluttonous selection with flavors that don't quite meet expectations. That is what we want, to feel that but without meat... I also prefer giving my money to a local small business and not to a mega chain that repeatedly ghosts vegans.

I stuck with the classics: Orange Chicken, Beef and Broccoli, and Kung Pao. All made with Taiwanese-style mock meats, which is to say the "chicken" will always be better than the "beef." Served with fried rice AND chow mein for ($20), this platter plus satellite scoop was eaten over two days by two people.

This isn't a place I would suggest going (too far) out of your way for, but if you're driving from downtown LA to a land of scant vegan Chinese food options (like San Diego) you would be only hurting yourself by not stopping here.

#VeganChineseFood
#VeganChinese
#ChineseAmericanFood

It's been far too long since I've been to @sushi.nekosan. In my absence the vegan options here have only gotten better! While all menu prices have risen, the vegan rolls are still almost half the price of fish. Surely reason enough for some customers to try veggie rolls... Especially ones that slay like this.

A classic since opening, the Sweetie Pie ($14) has evolved. Once a petit déjeuner, the roll is now fat with four lodes of fried Japanese sweet potatoes. Topped with avocado and lemons sliced invisibly thin under fluffy green onions and a drizzle of garlic cream

Bea-U-Tofu ($13) was made for me. All my favorite ingredients–fried tofu, avocado, kanpyo (gourd)–come sprinkled with sweet and salty seaweed furikake and just a touch of thick soy sauce.

I can't resist Sunomono Salad ($8). Slivers of cucumber in light rice vinegar and sesame. It's a gentle way to round out a sushi dinner without bulking up on rice. Like sashimi, but vegetables!

#VeganSushi
#VeganSushiinSanDiego
#LaJolla

The Christina’s Crispy ($14) at @sushi.nekosan exceeded all my expectations. Delicate, polished, grains lay beneath a golden landscape. Crispy crevasses filled with slivered avocado. Above, rings of jalapeño drown in torched miso mayo, bleeding sriracha, afloat through soy glaze. 

But it's the ponzu, invisible to the eye, that asserts itself. Punctuated by yuzu (a fragrance Japanese citrus), the ponzu cuts through everything, a pleasure rarely found in any sushi platter.

#VeganSushi
#VeganSushiinSanDiego
#LaJolla

location.city_name: Loving Hut - San Diego - North Park

social_posts.post_text:
It's simply the best! 

The Heavenly Salad ($13.95) at @lovinghut.sandiego is the edible definition of abundance. An exploding mass of shredded green papaya and cabbage comes laced with sweet peppers, carrots, tofu, and crushed peanuts with aromatic onions and mint. 

The sweet and sour tamarind dressing alone is worth the price. Usually you will receive two containers of it; more than enough for the already giant portion. In my house, not a drop is wasted as I use any leftovers on a less impressive homemade salad while dreaming I'm still in Loving Hut's heavenly arms.

#VeganSaladinSanDiego
#HeavenlySalad 
#LovingHut

I've walked in and right back out of @qin_west_noodle many times. There is nothing on the large wall menu, not even a description, to direct anyone towards ingredients. Let alone vegan options. But sometimes trusted vegans do the work for me, so thanks to @kittenxlady and @yiges I can (and you should) come enjoy the Liang Pi ($11.95)!

These naturally vegan "cold skin" noodles are made for these hot summer days. Thick, chewy, wheat noodles come slick with salty broth and topped with shredded cucumbers, crushed peanuts, and wilted bean sprouts. I ordered it extra spicy which it hardly is. Instead slicks of chili crunch holds numbing sichuan pepper and sesame, all eventually pooling at the bottom where I desperate dig with chopsticks to capture every last bit.

#VeganLiangPi
#VeganChineseinSanDiego
#VeganChineseFood
#LiangPi

From day one @tntsdpizza had the vision: Thick and Thin. Soon it will come to full fruition. I got a preview this week and it is 10/10. The ultimate thin crust should be hitting the main menu in a few weeks.

Yes they have a NYC-style thinner crust, but this ultra thin taven-style pizza compliments the fat Detroit-style beautifully. The thin crust dusted in cornmeal lends texture, but very little flavor, so all you taste are TNT's high quality topping. It's even delicious cold from the fridge the next day. I didn't know I needed this style in my life, and now I can't imagine pizza life without it.

#VeganPizza
#TavenStylePizza
#VeganPizzainSanDiego

The Pepper Glazed "Chicken" Strips ($16)  at @grainscafe continues to be a favorite. Mushrooms are whittled into two-bite strips, battered and fried then glazed in a sticky sweet soy sauce punctuated with black pepper. Charred cashews, red bells, and onions round out the dish along with a scoop of their signature purple rice blend.

#VeganIndianinSanDiego 
#Mushrooms 
#GrainsCafeSD

Though the hurricane hit lightly, the sunset before struck San Diego with neon force. I was lucky enough to catch it at a rooftop dinner for @veganinsandiego by @vegansupperclub_socal. Led by the talented @forageandflame / @iamchefkujo, with @vegnoutsd, we filled our hearts with light and our stomachs with vegan crab cakes and broccolini. 

Then, as
 we nibbled in chocolate chip cannoli and tiramisu, @alexisjoimusic turns the air electric.

#VeganSupperClub #VeganinSanDiego #VeganDinner #ForageandFlame #DinnerClub #SanDiegoSupperClub #SanDiego #SanDiegoExperences

Someone once told me I didn't like sandwiches... I liked "salad on bread." I think they meant that an insult, but it is 100% true. 

When given the choice between vegan egg and sausage or all the veggies on a bagel, I will always always always pick veggies. 

Cut thin and layered neatly so no one item slips out the back, crisp veggies highlight the delicate qualities of bread... or in this case a jalapeno bagel. Which is why my go-to at @benandesthers is The Veggie ($8.5).

#VeganBreafastinSanDiego 
#VeganBrunchinSanDiego
#AllTheveggies

Until this week I'd only had @companion.bread in grilled panini form. This week I devoured a lightly toasted rosemary potato sourdough loaf, purchased at @home.ec.store, spread thin with cashew cream and salted tomatoes.

The loaf screams with lactic and acetic acids. Each tart bite  activates salivation as my teeth cut through a tender crumb flecked with wheat germ and bran.

How lucky are we that @scratchhousesd used this bread only in their paninis. My favorites always revolve about @cheftonyhowe pairing his cultured white bean-based cheese with some form of pesto and seasonal veggies. Last month it was tarragon roasted zucchini and peppers, an unsimple delight. Each @firstfridaynightmarket brings a new play of fermentation and seasonality. I cannot wait to see what games he brings for us tonight. 

#VeganSandwichinSanDiego
#VeganGrilledCheese
#FirstFridayNightMarket

A stand out in the peculiarly popular vegan burger lexicon, @barkindred Eggroll Burger ($16) offers what all burgers crave but few restaurants give: crunch.

Here, a shumai prepped Impossible patty is wigged with shredded cabbage, pickled carrots, and cilantro. Together they ride the waves of two crispy eggroll skins through a spattering of sweet chili aioli. A textural experience once reserved only for Permanent Vacation but now available to the everyday guest.

#VeganBurgersinSanDiego 
#VeganBurger
#BarKindred

Many meals are ones of proximity, not the all consuming pursuit of the best. Because I spend a lot of my waking hours in University City, I'd like to believe I know all the vegan friendly meals in San Diego's golden triangle.

@staranisethaicuisine is my place of convenience. With a kindly marked menu that makes ordering lunch easy for most dietary needs. To me this is the menu all the restaurants should be reviewing if they care about accessibility. 

The food is fairly standard. The noodles are never overcooked, the veggies are generous and fresh, and when I ask for extra spicy I come away from my meal with a tear in my eye. I've been here enough to know the vegan trick–I asked for peanut sauce instead of the mayo-based dressing on the salad that comes with the $11.95 lunch special. On the side comes curried potato wonton crisps, that I've been assured of a vegan, along with a very sweet tamarind sauce. I wouldn't recommend driving out of your way for this, but if like me you work in one of the many offices around here Star Anise is a solid lunch or dinner option for everyone.

#VeganThaiinSanDiego
#VeganPadThai
#VeganThai

Nestled between San Diego's oldest machine shop and a live edge lumber yard, perpetually cozy @thegartenbaypark is the permanent home of @pizzacassettesd. Anchored by a roaring wood fire oven, the outdoor kitchen slings Neo-Neapolitan pizza. The line is punctuated with small plates and sandwiches.

The concise menu offers one vegan pizza–the Nonna ($16)–with double @biancodinapolitomatoes tomato sauce, oregano, basil, and roasted garlic. Excellent on its own, the frequent diner can dress it up with a soft house-made vegan mozzarella, arugula, shallots, or mushroom for +$2.

Some small plates are vegan by default. A loaf of pizza dough comes fired and unadorned with cups overflowing with hummus and eggplant caponata relish ($14) and citrus rind, rosemary, and thyme marinated olives ($7) are easy to share. Surrounding the courtyards sits @deftbrewing, @oddishwine, and @lostcausemeadery (made with honey) covering all tastes in alcoholic beverages.

#VeganPizza
#VeganPizzainSanDiego
#WoodFirePizza

I have no official knowledge... but with @donutpanicsd's recent announcement that they are closing because the shopping center that holds them, history's first Souplantain, and @thepurplemint is being torn down I'm going to be eating as many of these vegan Banh Mis ($9.75) and Double Delight rolls ($8.25) as possible.

While the Vietnamese community in San Diego is huge, there is limited competition for the best vegan banh mi. For me, this is it. A long crispy loaf comes spread with vegenaise and stuffed with well-seasoned with soy "chicken", "beef", or tofu. I prefer the tofu with julienned cucumber, pickled daikon and carrots under sprigs of cilantro and slivered jalapenos.

The Double Delight Roll is a stand out in San Diego. I don't know any other place here serving this brilliant combination of crispy eggroll wrapped in lettuce, herbs, bean sprouts, cucumber, and carrots swaddled tightly in rice paper skin. It satisfys my need to have it all, in one bite.

#VeganVietnameseinSanDiego
#VeganBanhMiinSanDiego
#VeganBanhMi

Yesterday, @civico1845 won Best Dish at the @delmarfest. I 100% agree.

I stepped onto the sunny turf of this new festival–driven by powerhouses of food and media–with a common goal: To recognize San Diego as a national culinary destination. 

As we weaved through the aisles of locally celebrated restaurants (many of which I know are vegan friendly) I scanned eagerly for dishes prepared without meat and dairy. We found very little. Except at Civico 1845. 

From the start this Little Italy anchor approached vegan food with sincerity and ambition. Pietro Gallo brings high standards to the business, elevating the vegan menu to match the quality of the kitchen's non-vegan dishes. So it was no surprise that they offered both a vegan and non-vegan dish at their booth–a fresh yet deeply seasoned bruschetta on crispy bread. 

To quote the current issue of @sandiegomag being handed out to the festival "[San Diego's] veggie food scene is strong enough that we can skip meat without missing a beat." I wholeheartedly concur. Which is why I thought more vendors would take Civico 1845's approach and offer a meat and a vegetable-forward bite. Clearly it made the Gallo brothers a stronger contender in the eyes, and mouths, of all who attended. Including me. 

Cheers to @civico1845 ❤️

#VeganinSanDiego
#VeganItalianinSanDiego
#VeganOptions

I enjoy giving food advice. I also enjoy receiving it. So when @diekpersonthedictator said that the Crispy Lemongrass Chicken over vermicelli ($14.5) was his favorite dish at @thepurplemint, I had to try it.

The wide bowl is brimming with thin rice noodles topped with fresh and crispies like lettuce, cucumber, bean sprouts pickled carrots and daikon with a sweet and sour dressing. On top is crispy soy chicken (you have to specifically ask for crispy, the standard is sauteed) coated in a sticky sweet sauce threaded with lemongrass and chilies. 

It's regrettable that it took me until the point of the restaurant moving (they do say they are hoping to find a new location soon) to find this dish. I suggest, now that you know, you don't wait as long as I did.

#VeganVietnameseinSanDiego
#VeganVietnmeseFood
#SanDiegoVietnamese

Cleveland's Emperors Palace holds such a special place in my heart. Gilded in golden pride, this classic Chinese-American restaurant sits in a desolate Chinatown just east of Cleveland's downtown. Even if the dining room is empty (a tragedy on a Friday afternoon) the staff is prompt and kind and swiftly serves food oozing creativity.

The menu is huge and does not shy away from vegan options. Without explanation dishes like General Tso's Veggie Chicken ($14.95) arrives as big beautiful balls of tofu and vegetables, bound with starch, then deep fried and glazed in a sweet and spicy sauce over broccoli. The bean curd sheet dishes display so much more moxie than any vegan Chinese dish I've seen in a big city. Thin sheets of tofu are layered with seaweed and folded into cakes, pan-fried, and drowned in your choice of sauce (I chose the house brown gravy $14.95) all over very fresh, lightly steamed, vegetables. 

Any Chinese restaurant could be doing this. But they are not. Why, I don't know. But I'm so glad that Emperor's Palace exists... even if it means I have to fly to Cleveland to enjoy good vegan Chinese food.

#VeganChineseFood
#ChineseFood
#Yuba

Yes I am jealous of vegan Chinese food in Cleveland. It overwhelms me thinking how historically vegetable-friendly Chinese cooking is yet most Chinese-American restaurants (at least in Southern California) reflect back the contemporary global hunger for factory farmed meat.

But then I head to Cleveland and, randomly, the closest restaurant to where I'm staying has this: Suanjiang Noodle ($18). Thick ramen noodles rise from a distinctly spiced Chinese broth. Small pools of chili oil shimmer where surface tension breaks for bite-sized tofu skin sticks and whole cloves of sweet black garlic. Finely chopped carrot, potato, celery, and bok choy challenge my chopsticks while the frilly light and dark bodies of wood ear mushrooms come willingly.

With it I ordered the playful Ganguo Tater ($12). Factory scrapped potatoes formed into tots come glazed in a thin–but bold–layer of spices seared into place by a wok. Purple and green onions weave between.

Creativity abounds in America's mid-sized cities. I see risks taken here that no one would dare consider in San Diego where the price to start a food business is so high. So we get a press parade of burger joints and valle de guadalupe inspired plates while the dishes that challenge food norms arise away from the oceans and next to a Great Lake. 

#VeganChineseFood
#VeganNoodles
#VeganCLE #ClevelandFood #ClevelandVegan

I am 120 miles away from @heysunshinekitchen, yet I think about it everyday. I took this photo before eating the food so I'm sorry that you cannot see the chopped up chickpea patty hidden under those mint leaves. I am absolutely obsessed with it.

I am usually very good at identifying ingredients... but I was so overwhelmed by the deliciousness of whatever the @sporkfoods sisters are putting into their chickpea patty that all I could taste was my own happiness (which is not an ingredient... or is it 😏).

This new restaurant is a welcomed addition to my hometown. Even if I can't afford to live there, I now know I will always eat well when I visit.

#VeganCulverCity #CulverCity #VeganBowl #VegetableBowl #Salad #ChickpeaPatty

Recently I approached a pizza buffet with a bad attitude. I assumed the table of automatically replenishing pizza trays would have nothing for me.

A co-worker–who knows I can get a bit pouty/hangry–flagged me down because there was a vegan option. A Neapolitan pizza swirled in red sauce and roasted vegetables. There were two pieces left. I grabbed them both–a luckily move because I didn't see any more veggie pizza the rest of the event.

I'm told at these events to "just ask" for a vegan pizza. But it defeats that whole point of a buffet. And it feels crappy to break the work flow of an hourly employee to demand they make me something special.... then have to linger, waiting for my pizza, hoping no one eats it before I do. 

I hear over and over, "but the regular people don't want vegan pizza." I think caterers vastly overestimated the pickiness of customers at a pizza buffet. People like pizza, even without cheese. Those in charge choose cheese, not the people. 

A cheeseless Neapolitan pizza is not even a strange ask. Mariana is an icon of menus around the world. Buffets offer the illusion of choice, but monotonously topped pizza deny real (political!) choice–not just for this winy vegan, but for others whose health and lifestyle don't require EVERY bite of food be smothered in cheese. 

Today I found myself at another pizza buffet. Thanks to a receptionist who always ensures there are options for the multiple vegans in our office, vegan pizza was on the table for everyone (no need for me to ask then have to wait around). While it may have been the least popular pizza, it wasn't just the vegans who ate it–it was 80% gone before the first vegan took a slice. They brought out another.... then another. 

There are always leftovers at these events. On principle I wanted the pizza crew to see the vegan pizza was eaten, completely. Though very full, I saw there was one slice left. I headed towards it. Before I got there a non-vegan coworker grabbed the last vegan slice from the otherwise meat and cheese filled table.  I smiled, so hard, as she walked away with it.

#VeganPizza 
#VeganPizzainSanDiego
#VeganWorkLunch

I put @beaudub on the spot about the history of the pickleback. Not in a gotcha way but to help me feel less crazy when I say: I was there. In 2006 I was frequently at the Bushwick Country Club, a Brooklyn dive bar known for big buck hunter, DIY mini golf, and for coining the term Pickleback. In its pure form, it's a shot of whiskey (Old Crow Bourbon) followed by a shot of pickle juice (McClure's spicy dill). The shooter is now etched into the drinker's lexicon next to the slippery nipple and cement mixer. 

You can find the shot duo in many places. And now it sits before me, reimagined for the @eatpuesto / San Diego market. The Pineapple Pickleback ($12) is a highbrow/lowbrow experience of quality blanco tequila with a chaser of sweet and lightly spicy pineapple and poblano pickle brine and slices of fresh pineapple. I loved it. 

To see the dram of choice for the Y2K misfits I once ran with continue to evolve makes me feel like I am (we are) part of an unbound tradition that will outlive us all. Even though I was clueless, in the front booth with a vodka soda and basket of cheesy poofs or out back playing ice cream cone mini golf, while history happened around me.

#Pickleback
#NewClassicCocktail
#BarShot

You don't have to be veg to know the classics. That same "vegetarian pizza" served coast to coast or that same rarely ordered  "vegetarian" sandwich lingering on deli menus.

The same is true of the veggie taco. So when I saw two veggie tacos on @eatpuesto 's menu I ordered both... to compare. Both require holding the cheese to make it vegan.

The long standing Verduras ($8) offers classic "veggie taco" fillings like peppers, zucchini, potatoes, corn, and nopales topped with avocado and a wisp of a squash blossom. A collection of juicy vegetables served juicy, it's a conventional take on a vegetarian standard.

The newest taco on the menu, Vegetable Mole Verde ($9), comes piled with crispy charred broccoli florets and soft cauliflower chunks rising from a pool of rich broccoli kale mole verde. The mole, made creamy with sunflower seeds, steeps up into the cruciferous crevasse under drops of deep red, oil-based, flax seed salsa macha. A scattering of hemp seeds and cilantro finish it off. This is a taco for today. Good vegetables, treated and seasoned well. The Vegetable Mole is on the menu for a limited time, a potential tragedy! If the choice were mine, I'd retire the Verduras and let this textural delight stay.

If you find yourself here being treated (or treating yourself) to a nice lunch or dinner, these are your vegan options:

Vegan as-is:
• Chips + molcajete salsa
• Classic guac
• Nogada guac

Hold the cheese to make vegan:
• Mushroom taco 
• Verduras taco
• Vegetable Mole Taco
• Chopped Salad
• Jalapeño caesar

#VeganTacosinSanDiego
#VeganTacos
#Puesto

A breakfast burrito the way I would make it–loaded with tofu and tater tots! With bits of smokey @thrillingfoods vegan bacon and chipotle sauce, I appreciate this filling fist full of food on a weekday morning when I have neither the time or energy to make real food for myself. 

Available at @sandiegoveganmarket
Mon: 10am - noon
Wed - Fri: 9am - noon

Memories can be too kind to the past, so things lost always seem... ideal. That may be why I took pause before heading to Oceanside's @erisfoodco, the cafe that rose from the remains of Eve. 

I was immediately welcomed by the chef and owner, Scott. I recognize him but he has no reason to recognize me. Drifting towards the menu he pop he head around and recommended all the specials. Like a self-important Instagram a-hole I asked which photographed best. Because I already had a good feeling and knew I had one shot to convince you and I to come (back) here.

He suggested the Asada Bowl ($20). A massive dish–easily two meals–of short grain brown rice, golden sweet potatoes, housemade asada spiced seitan, and so on. This one dish is better than everything I've ever had by Scott before (Eve and Trilogy). Here, with a dedicated crew, the food aims to serve a hungry local audience with made-from-scratch quality control (even the hamburger buns are made in house) and generous portions intended to fill us up. Which I hope will happen for me (and you) sometime again soon.

PS - Cheers to @whatcameradoyouhave for their very strong endorsement of Eris. I happened to sit next to them at a dinner party months ago. That happenstance was the reason I came here during my rare travel to north county.

#VeganinSanDiego
#VeganOceanside 
#Vegan

Navigating a Japanese market with no understanding of the language can be intimidating. There's a well-earned perception that Japanese food has a lot of hidden fish. But once you learn the shelves there are many gems. Here are a few of mine from @nijiya__market on Convoy St.

 1-2: I got two meals out of an affordable selection of vegan sides:

3: • Vegan Fried Chicken ($3.60)
4: • Sesame Spinach ($2.99) 
• Organic Brown Rice ($1.39)
• Pickles - cucumbers, cabbage, eggplant, carrots  ($3.49)
• Vegan Potato Salad (homemade)

5: @MeijiTofu - Ultra soft, ultra fresh. This tofu is delicious cold, directly from the case or dressed lightly with good shoyu, chili crunch, sauteed mushrooms, or served sweet with jam.

6: Raindrop Jelly - A viral dish from the early days of Instagram. This delicate water and agar cake is served with roasted soybean powder and brown sugar syrup.

7: Mitarashi dango - 🍡 So popular there is an emoji for them. I adore these sweet rice dumplings (not mochi) in a sweet, sticky, salty sauce (they also come smothered in red bean paste).

8: @sunnoodles - My favorite ramen noodle, by far. Made in Southern California and served by some of the best local ramen shops.

9: Vegan ponzu - This light salty citrus sauce is perfect for tempura and dumplings.

10: For my gluten-free followers, these cassava based wrappers taste just like traditional gyoza ☺️

#NijiyaMarket #JapaneseMarket
#VeganJapaneseinSanDiego

Without hesitation, I recommend meeting up at @tntsdpizza with pizza consultant (and long time friend) @slowrisepizza. 

We ordered one of every style of crust (as one does when dining out with a dough doctor!) but my heart was set on just one pizza: a preview of the Vegan Birria Detroit made in collaboration with @eattacotarian that will be sold  this weekend.

**Friday 11/3 - Sunday 11/5 only**

An impossibly cheesey blanket falls across the delicious rise of thick pan baked crust. On top a blend of chickpeas and jackfruit steeped in a rich Birria chili broth with red onions and a drizzled of cilantro lime sauce. The combination is both bold and delicate, with complex seasoning that somehow only got better when devouring the leftovers the next day (not something I have ever say about tacos 🤪). 

You should definitely plan to try this over the weekend!

#VeganPizza
#BirriaPizza
#VeganPizzainSanDiego

I nonchalantly pulled into the parking lot at 4616 El Cajon Blvd–the announced new address of Purple Mint–to spy! Slowly, I walked past the restaurant's windows but then pretended (to no one) that I was really there to visit their strip mall neighborhood, @parisbakerysd.

I've been before and I know what I want: Cha Chay ($7). This banana wrapped seasoned yuba (tofu skin) loaf is one of my favorite savory treats. I figured I might as well get a No.9 Vegetarian Banh Mi ($7) too. Seeing the tofu loaf in my hand, the woman taking my order asks if I want the cha chay as my sandwich protein instead of the standard veggie floss. Heck yeah I do!

Tofu skins compressed into a loaf turns into a thick protein that holds up so well against the crusty edge of a baguette. Delicate black pepper and white sugar seasoning folds create a soft yet flaky texture that is, as intended, similar to meat.

Sliced thick and topped with pickles carrot and daikon radish with sprigs of cilantro this Banh Mi is a simple straightforward pleasure.

PS - They did confirm that their housemate baguettes and veggie sandwich (This one and the traditional No. 9 Chay) are vegan as is 😉☺️

#VeganSandwich
#VeganBanhMi
#VeganBanhMiinSanDiego
#VeganSandwichinSanDiego
#nationalsandwichday

San Diego's @boardandbrew has been “Keepin’ it Real" since 1979... and it shows! 

The veganized Veggie Supreme starts with removing two layers of cheese and mayo from a vegetarian sandwich. Such a throwback move. You are left with a generous portion of avocado with lettuce, sprouts, onion, cucumber, and those hard pale tomatoes that seem only to be sold to sandwich shops. There is no seasoning beyond the sweet wheat bread. 

Their signature sauce is conveniently vegan. The beloved sauce the subject of copycat recipes blogs and Reddit posts all trying to recreate the pale orange, viscous, emulsified canola oil and sugar. This was my first time tasting it... and it took all of my core strength not to burst out laughing. Paired with the already sweet bread, it was like eating dinner and dessert at the same time. 

There have been many changes to culture and food service catalogues since 1979. And all of those changes are very real too.

#VeganSandwichinSanDiego
#VeganSandwich
#BoardandBrew

Years ago I wrote an ode to the black bean burger at @plantpowerfastfood. The next day it was discontinued.

I miss that burger. But not that specific burger. 

I miss having the option of a bean-based patty; one where I can see the beans. Pop-food voices love to lambast the squishy texture of a bean patty, but like, it is smashed beans... that is what the texture is supposed to be. How can you make fun of food for being itself?

Because this Hippy Patty is, yes, soft and squishy. It compresses under the crispy shell of onion rings and lettuce lubricated with barbecue sauce. It crumbles a bit out of the back end, but makes a valiant effort to hold together. Bits of cashews give variation to the softness and smokey peppers add that vague sense of char that so many people mistake for the taste of meat.

While not necessarily something I'll be running back for–I'm not keen on any burger and find their popularity in America food culture bazaar–this is a long needed revival on the Plant Power menu. When I order a PP burger next, it will be with this patty.

Sweet potato fries are a very welcomed addition as well. The thin cut sweet potatoes seem lightly battered and fried, similar to Native Foods but without the tarragon seasoning salt... depending on how you feel about tarragon, that may be good or may be bad.

#VeganBurgersinSanDiego 
#PlantPowerFastFood 
#VeganBurger #BlackBeanPatty

Thai food in America is, by design, homogeneous. Because of this I never recommend Thai restaurants to visitors who have their own local Thai restaurants serving an almost identical menu. But exceptions exist! San Diego's exception is @so_saap.

The menu offers all the classics–pad Thai, fried rice, curry, and so on... @kimonosrock and I skipped right past those to feast on the mostly Laotian vegan menu.

We meandered over the four vegan Laab ($14.99) options. "The mushroom is my favorite," the waitress nudged us. Sold! Obscure by petals of mint and cilantro lies an evolution of this  traditionally centered on ground meat "national dish". Here, diced mushrooms are saturated in a sweet, savory, and sour lime and vegan fish sauce that is impossible not to love. Cooked down until the flesh turns chewy and skin is glazed with caramelized dressing. Finished with the faint crunch of ground roasted rice powder with slivers of red onion, curly lettuce, and large slabs of cucumber. 

Rice salads of all persuasions are personal favorites. Nam Khao ($14.99) starts with boats of romaine lettuce which we filled with crushed fragrant fried rice balls seared with fermented mushrooms (mimicking som moo, a fermented sour pork sausage). Laced with coconut, herbs, chili, and peanuts it proved the mildest dish of the meal while still being bolder than any other version I've sampled in the city.

#VeganinSanDiego
#VeganLaab
#VeganNamKhao

Boat Noodles ($15), derived from the rich brothy noodles served from boats roaming the Bangkok canals, @so_saap pulls this dish ashore. Their veganized broth reduces vegetables to the depths of their flavor potential... without molding their natural earthy characteristics into imitations of animals (seeing as the signature ingredient of ready boat noodles is blood, I thank them for this approach).

The tall bowl holds an abundant weave of thin rice noodles, herbs, and tender greens wilting in the steam. Soy "beef" slices and vegan "beef" meatballs round out the dish along with a side of fresh beans sprouts, Thai basil, and lime.

The waitress brought us bowls to share because we were sharing everything. I'm not entirely sure if this is actually meant to be a sharing dish (since similar, but different, dishes like pho or ramen are generally a single serving). I am grateful she did because I cannot imagine anyone could eat this whole bost alone.

#VeganBoatNoodles
#VeganThaiinSanDiego
#VeganSoupinSanDiego

No "fish sauces" have hit my visceral fear of fish like this.

@so_saap Laos style Papaya Salad ($14.99) is... shocking. Shredded green papaya, green beans, and tomatoes come macerated in lime and the funkiest fermented sauce I've had the panic and pleasure of eating. @kimonosrock–who synchronously is studying the vast world of wine–correctly identified the district flavors of aged tropical fruit. Mango, perhaps papaya... "It's pineapple," the waitress corrects us. Of course it is, but if I wasn't confident this So Saap is serious about vegan options, there is little else that could convince me this is not fish. 

To that point, in the vegan condiment tray, there is prik nam blah–veg fish sauce with chilies.  Which takes a lighter approach with mostly notes of salt and sugar (and lots of fresh chopped chilies). This is a favorite table addition, one that is a standard in my house, and I am beyond grateful that I can indulge here... even though the food here really doesn't need any condiments added. It's quite perfect as served.

#VeganLaos
#VeganFishSauce
#VeganThaiinSanDiego

Thanksgiving spent with the best food and best creatures. @kirstinanngreen and I focused on bringing richly developed flavor and tons of texture to the traditional table of soft sides. 

Fluffy red potato holds warm within the smashed shards of skin, baked in a lot of olive oil until golden and crisp. Served with dark gravy studded with diced mushrooms that amplifies the buttery nature of potatoes. 

Brussel sprouts cuddle in a warm dressing of miso, maple, and rice vinegar. My baby bella and oyster mushrooms bread pudding–spiked with real black truffle, caramelized onion, basil, and @goodtastefarm sage and rosemary–holds a sourdough custard core under rising peeks of bread crusted in mushroom seasoning, crushed red pepper, and thin sliced green onion.

With it, a crisp salad–pulled from @kirstinanngreen 's garden moments before serving–is dressed simply with good olive and sweet balsamic. Cranberry sauce comes two ways: sweetly stewed with California oranges and coconut sugar or all of the above with a generous amount of chopped bird's eye chilis.

For dessert, leftover cranberries become an almond flour upside down cake served with frothy coconut milk and crisp ginger snaps.

With it all, four cats and kittens kept us company. Along with glasses full of pet nat wine, housemade kombucha, and fresh water for all. A lovely evening with @brittsters72 , @allmandingerr , and @theveggievoyager ❤️

#veganthanksgiving #veganholiday #vegancelebration

I hate being "that vegan" in a restaurant. Thanks @alegrastickney for reminding me that it's ok to ask for what I want.

Pictured here is the @gravityheights Hot Agave ($17) pizza with red sauce, garlic, arugula ,(+$1), and cashew ricotta finished with a sweet and spicy drizzle which is no longer on the printed menu but they can still make... If you ask 😄

With it we shared the sweet Cranberry Apple Salad ($14.5). Lacey lettuce made sweet with fruits, candied walnuts, and crispy quinoa (hold the goat cheese). Not pictured is the bowl of fries devoured in a fever dream of too much work to do before yesterday.

#VeganPizza #VeganPizzainSanDiego #ArgulaonPizza

I went vegetarian in 1992. This was the pre-internet everyone-knows-everything era so my understanding didn't scratch deeper than flesh. It was less years ago than fingers that I snapped into an awareness of invisible ingredients like fish sauce and chicken broth. I most certainly had been eating fish sauce laced Thai food for decades, I simply didn't know to ask.

Now I know, now I ask, and now my taste is accustomed to fish sauce free Thai food. I used to be the first to say the vegan versions taste exactly the same, but Pad Thai (with chicken seitan $13.99) at @so_saap may have just changed my whole attitude. The faint hint of funky fermented sauce–in this case pineapple not fish–flickers thought noodles saturated in tangy tamarind and salty soy sauce, framing the flavors in ways I didn't realize they wanted. So Saap's Pad Thai unlocked decades of blissfully unaware vegetarian who unknowingly ate fish sauce memories. This this this tastes traditional, yet veganized. 

Though I am squeamish about bringing vegan fish sauce into my home, I must go back and buy the pineapple sauce from World Foods (5245 El Cajon Blvd) because fermented foods need not be cut from vegan Thai cooking. Not from commercial kitchens, not from my own.

#VeganThaiinSanDiego
#VeganPadThai
#VeganinSanDiego

Normally I'm the one who picks the food. I pick the restaurant, I pick the dishes. But this month has been a lot. Overwhelmed my husband offered to pick up dinner. When he asked what I wanted I said "whatever"...and I meant it.

So he picked a Buffalo Gal Detroit-style pizza ($32) from @tntsdpizza. Something I likely wouldn't pick (are we not all–in theory–tired of buffalo everything these days?) but that's exactly why it delights. Thick crust comes loaded with lightly spiced, extra tangy, soy curls and pepperoncini with green onions and tons of vegan mozzarella smothered in herby vegan ranch. It's acid-forward (my mouth salivates just writing this) followed by mouth costed fat; each bite is a new cycle of sharp then southing flavors and emotions. Because what is more comforting to Americans than pizza. In times of stress and in time of joy, it's the food that we as a national turn to. TNT Pizza is basically the most effective therapeutic made in San Diego.

#VeganPizzainSanDiego
#VeganPizza
#TNTpizza

There are many vegan options at @goicuon.us but I can't move past the Combo 3 ($11.99) add Bean Curd Skin & Crispy Snack Spring Rolls ($3.95). An assembly of textures–from deep fried to fresh noodle skin–it satisfies regardless of my craving.

Back in the salad days of pre-2020, @goicuon.us was my go-to treat as I lingered over summer cucumbers and winter squash at the Hillcrest Farmers Market.

I had been waiting and waiting for a vegan Pickle Pie NY to show up in the slice case on a day I'm at @tntsdpizza. It's a provocative combination, one that I was hesitant to commit to a whole pizza of just for me. Then I found myself with a trusting group of 8 letting me order for the table, so seized the opportunity. 

The idea of a pickle pizza can come across as low brow. This is anything but. Previous pickled pies I've tried rely on the pickles alone to carry the name; TNT's version is cleverly crafted with layers of garlic, fresh dill, and herby ranch to reinforce pickleness in each bite. The crust is studded in everything bagel seasoning–with high notes of salt, garlic, and onion–that reinforce the concept to the last bite. It's a brilliant pie. There was no need for me to hedge towards ordering it.

As always, TNT has vegan substitutes (not omissions) for everything. The key ingredients of the Pickle Pie NY are vegan as is, so to sub in their quality vegan cheese and ranch makes this an easy pizza to share with everyone, vegan or not.

#VeganPizza 
#VeganPizzainSanDiego 
#PicklePizza

A simple act, one they may not even realize is monumental, elevates the 辛い野菜 Spicy Garlic Vegan Ramen ($14.99) at @facingeastsd: 3 Veggie Dumplings.

Fried and floating in black garlic oil miso broth, they are a veggie-forward break from cottony tofu and wilted spring mix. One that adds textural complexity, doesn't' mimic meat, and is a natural presence in a Japanese kitchen.

Paired with the weighty cut of bok choy, slivered green onion, pops of corn, and wilted bean sprouts threaded through spinach noodles, this vegan as-is dish is a pleasure to add to my growing knowledge of good vegan ramen in San Diego.

#VeganRameninSanDiego
#VeganRamen
#Ramen

@erisfoodco is a refreshing space of abundance and flavor. In these days of shrinking portions and quality cutbacks, owner/chef Scott's truly scratch-made versions suffer none of this.

Multiple people have insisted I try the Chikun Parmesan ($22) and now I must insist you do too. A fat house-made (I think seitan) chicken-style cutlet comes fried in a thick bloom of sunflower seed mozzarella resting in well-developed marinara sauce over whirls of spaghetti slick with pesto. Three cuts of garlic bread are best saved for the end to sop up every last glisten of sauce.

At this age, I cannot live on carbs alone. So we shared a Chop Chop Salad ($16). A mound of kale, arugula, red cabbage, and radishes arrives dressed in sunflower dill dressing with chickpeas tumbling down. Pungent points of olives, pickles, and pepperoncini tingle the tongue as teeth crunch through sunflower and pumpkins seeds. We ate half of each and took home leftovers so flavorful I merely added some more lettuce to turn it into one more meal for two.

#VeganinSanDiego

There will always be non-vegan bakeries (and restaurants and markets). If you appreciate fully vegan businesses, now is the time to support them.

@hazelandjadebakery poignantly put it "we want to deserve to be here." They do. They consistently put out outstanding pastries, oozing vegan butter, punctuated with fruits, chocolate, and cheese.

My personal favorite is the Croissant Bun (pictured in back). Fakey laminated dough cupping seasonal fruits–in this photo it's apples–under and drift of icing. Heat and metal turns the outside into a sticky sweet caramelized shell. Crack it open to reach the fruit your tenderheart holds.

This bun is one of the great joys of San Diego. One to enjoy now before it fades away.

At most restaurants, I am a cheap date. 

Like a relic, the key on the @cutwatertastingroom menu includes a vegan "V" but no dishes are marked with it. They once had vegan entrees, but all that's left is the quintessential option at a non-vegan restaurant: Fries and a salad.

Which is not a complaint. I love both! But by only offering vegans the lowest priced items, it's a missed opportunity. I wanted to spend more, but there was nothing left to spend it on.

I adored the Pomegranate Pear Salad ($13). Lacy lettuce balancing pomegranate seeds and candied walnuts with slivered pears (the menu recently moved on to persimmons) all tossed in a golden balsamic vinaigrette (hold the cheese to make vegan). On top I got the cheapest/only vegan add-in, avocado (+$2.5).

With it @alegrastickney_ and I shared an array of classic and tiki-inspired cocktails swirling with house distilled liquor. Heady and sweet much like the canned cocktails you've surely encountered in everyday life by now. Back lit beauties, piled with pebble ice and curated garnishes, presented in a sleek open-air dining room that is absolutely packed after the working day is done.
